              <otmi:snippet>Also, as the K + selectivity decreases, a new feature emerges in these channels â€” Ca 2+ permeability</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Although an extracellular Ca 2+ -binding site has been proposed in many Ca 2+ -permeable channels, this site has always been thought to involve the carboxylate of an acidic residue in the selectivity filter</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Although the sequence similarity is weaker between CNG channels and voltage-gated Ca 2+ and Na + channels ( Fig. 2 ), a similar role for an acidic residue has been suggested in those channels </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Another intriguing finding in the NaK structure was the presence of a divalent binding site, capable of binding Ca 2+ , at the extracellular entrance to the NaK selectivity filter</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Both are tetrameric (with four subunits) or pseudotetrameric channels with a &quot;selectivity filter&quot; in the narrowest part of the pore, formed from the P-loop between the inner and outer transmembrane helices ( Fig. 1 )</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Both the TRP and CNG channels are highly permeable to Ca 2+ </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Ca 2+ permeability is thought to arise at high concentrations of Ca 2+ from the binding of multiple Ca 2+ ions that exhibit mutual repulsion </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Can the charge on this residue exhibit a through-space electrostatic interaction with ions in the pore? Do mutations of this residue alter the backbone structure and so indirectly alter ion-binding sites? Could the position of this acidic residue be different in open channels? And, is the NaK channel pore structure representative of eukaryotic CNG channels and voltage-gated Ca 2+ channels? As always, X-ray crystallography has answered many questions with astonishing clarity, but there are yet more to be addressed.</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Channels selective for potassium ions allow K + to exit the cell, causing hyper-polarization of the membrane and decreasing the cell&apos;s electrical excitability </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Channels selective for sodium ions allow Na + to enter the cell, causing depolarization of the membrane</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Each subunit has two membrane-spanning helices, M1 (outer helix) and M2 (inner helix), with an intervening P-loop ( Fig. 1 )</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Given their opposite roles, it is surprising that many Na + channels and K + channels are structurally related</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Highly K + -selective channels almost all possess the amino-acid signature sequence TVGYG in their selectivity filter</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In CNG channels, this acidic residue has also been proposed to be involved in regulating a number of permeation and blocking properties, including ion selectivity, divalent block, proton block and state-dependent tetracaine block </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In NaK, these two binding sites are replaced by a &quot;pore vestibule&quot; that can accommodate just a single ion ( Fig. 2 )</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In the case of neurons, this can trigger the cell to fire an action potential or release a neurotransmitter</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>In this issue, Jiang and colleagues ( page 570 ) reveal the first atomic structure of a channel with both Na + and K + permeability, the NaK channel from Bacillus cereus </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Ion channels are nature&apos;s gatekeepers: by allowing certain ions to pass across the membrane and excluding others, these proteins control the electrical state of the cell</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>It is composed of four subunits surrounding a central pore</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Jiang and colleagues reveal that the properties of Na + permeability and Ca 2+ block also seem to be shared by the NaK channel from B. cereus </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Molecular dynamics simulations implicated the first two binding sites in the selectivity filter of KcsA as the most K + - selective sites </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>NaK contains a selectivity filter sequence (TVGD) similar to that of most CNG channels (TIGE)</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Overall, the backbone structure of NaK is very similar to that of KcsA</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Paradoxically, Ca 2+ also blocks some of these channels at low concentrations</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Surprisingly, in the NaK structure this acidic residue, the aspartate, is facing away from the pore, and the binding site for Ca 2+ is formed by backbone carbonyls of the glycine residues at the extracellular end of the selectivity filter sequence</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The NaK structure diverges from KcsA in the selectivity filter</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The approximately 1,000:1 selectivity for K + over Na + of these channels arises from the K + selectivity of these sites and mutual repulsion between the K + ions bound to the sites </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The finding that the aspartic-acid residue in the NaK structure does not bind directly to the ions raises some interesting questions</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The hyperpolarization-activated HCN channels exhibit only about a 4:1 selectivity for K + over Na + , and the transient receptor potential (TRP) channels and cyclic nucleotide-gated (CNG) channels are equally selective for K + and Na + (refs 7 , 8 )</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The pore is lined by the M2 on the intracellular side, and by the P-loops on the extracellular side</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The similarity of selectivity filter sequences to the signature sequence, however, breaks down as channels become more Na + and Ca 2+ permeable ( Fig. 2 )</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The structural basis for K + selectivity is well established, mainly from work on the bacterial K + channel KcsA (refs 2â€“4 ), but the basis for Na + per-meability has been unclear</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The structure of the NaK channel, therefore, gives us our first glimpse into how differences in the sequence of the selectivity filter can produce varying Na + and Ca 2+ permeability in these channels</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>The third and fourth ion-binding sites are structurally very similar to their counterparts in KcsA, but can bind to K + and Na + with virtually no rearrangements in the protein</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>These differences might make the NaK pore seem shorter in electrophysiological and flux studies than the K + channel pore </otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This ion is not bound by carbonyl oxygens, as it would be in KcsA, because of a rearrangement in the backbone of the selectivity filter, presumably caused by the change of tyrosine (Y) in KcsA to aspartate (D) in NaK</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This motif is shared by many other ion channels that range in selectivity from highly K + -selective to highly Na + - or Ca 2+ -selective ( Fig. 2 , overleaf)</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>This property is finely honed in the voltage-gated Ca 2+ channels to produce extremely high Ca 2+ -selectivity</otmi:snippet>
              <otmi:snippet>Together with the hydroxyl group of the threonine (T), the backbone carbonyls from the signature sequence form four K + -binding sites in the selectivity filter ( Fig. 2 )</otmi:snippet>
            </otmi:snippets>
          </otmi:section>
        </otmi:section>
